{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Lower the legal maximum volume off all emergency vehicles to 95dB",
        "additional_details": "Exposure to sounds at or above 85 decibels (approximately the level of a vacuum cleaner) can cause hearing loss. - hearsmart.org\r\n\r\nThe dB is a logarithmic unit based on base 10 meaning a sound at 50 dB is noticeably twice as loud as 40dB\r\n\r\nThis means a sound of 125dB is noticeably 16 times louder than 85dB(the noise level which hearing damage can start)\r\n\r\nIf sirens were limited to 95dB it would have much less of a negative effect on the public yet still be just as effective as clearing the road",
        "background": "I have autism and loud noises aren't just a botherance to me, it's painful and leave me in a vulnerable depressed state, often unable to speak for quite some time, this is a sensory overload. I understand why they are necessary, I just don't believe they need to be this loud.",
